# Seed Ideas

> **What this file is.** A backlog of product ideas you've already had in your head — half-baked or fully formed — that you'd want `/discover` to weight its brainstorming toward. This is NOT the same as `ideas/` at the repo root (those are *validated* idea cards from formal discovery cycles); this file is your mental staging area before any of them have been formalized.
>
> **Why this matters for product discovery.** Without seed ideas, `/discover` bootstraps from broad capability shifts + your interests (from `INTERESTS.md`) alone. Cards it brainstorms will be plausible but generic. **With seed ideas**, the reviewer reads "what's already on your mind" and uses adjacency to produce candidates that resonate with you — and that fit founder-market patterns the reviewers are unlikely to kill in the validation phase.
>
> **How to populate.** Just dump ideas. One per section. Don't worry about completeness — even a one-liner is useful. Claude formats your raw text into the structure below when you onboard (or you can edit this file directly any time).
>
> **Gitignored.** Your seed ideas stay local; nothing here enters git.

---

## Idea — <one-line title>

**What it is** (1-2 sentences): *e.g., "A platform where independent music teachers can manage their student rosters, scheduled lessons, payment collection, and progress notes — currently they're stitching together 4 separate tools."*

**Who it's for**: *e.g., "Solo piano / guitar / voice teachers with 10-40 active students."*

**Why I think about it**: *e.g., "My sister teaches music and shows me the spreadsheet she uses every month — visibly frustrated. She's not technical so DIY tools don't fit."*

**What I'd want to test first** (the riskiest assumption — the thing I most want to be true): *e.g., "Whether teachers will actually pay for this vs. accepting their spreadsheet friction. Music teachers are price-sensitive."*

**Where I'd find first users**: *e.g., "r/musicteachers, music-teacher Facebook groups, local conservatories."*

